    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-35555' data-commentid="35555" data-postid="439" data-belowelement="comment-35555" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Rachel" aria-label='Reply to Rachel'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-35431" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01597075882921799324" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">John D</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2012/01/i-am-here-to-tell-you/#comment-35431"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2012-01-26T23:52:23-05:00">Thursday, January 26, 2012 at 11:52 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>@Thinking of the days: Maple syrup&#39;s graded on colour, with the darker stuff having a more intense flavour. So U.S. Grade B maple syrup is pretty dark stuff. It&#39;s the kind that&#39;s better for use in baking, as opposed to just putting on pancakes.</p>
<p>I&#39;m assuming that maple syrup purchased in the U.K. is labelled with the standards of the country of origin, which means it&#39;s more likely to be Canadian than American. If the syrup on your shelves is from Canada you can try to find #1 Medium (B) or #2 Amber (C). (I doubt we export much #3 Dark (D), because not much gets made and demand may not be that high).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-35431' data-commentid="35431" data-postid="439" data-belowelement="comment-35431" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to John D" aria-label='Reply to John D'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-35556" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01597075882921799324" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">John D</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2012/01/i-am-here-to-tell-you/#comment-35556"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2012-01-26T23:52:23-05:00">Thursday, January 26, 2012 at 11:52 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>@Thinking of the days: Maple syrup&#39;s graded on colour, with the darker stuff having a more intense flavour. So U.S. Grade B maple syrup is pretty dark stuff. It&#39;s the kind that&#39;s better for use in baking, as opposed to just putting on pancakes.</p>
<p>I&#39;m assuming that maple syrup purchased in the U.K. is labelled with the standards of the country of origin, which means it&#39;s more likely to be Canadian than American. If the syrup on your shelves is from Canada you can try to find #1 Medium (B) or #2 Amber (C). (I doubt we export much #3 Dark (D), because not much gets made and demand may not be that high).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-35556' data-commentid="35556" data-postid="439" data-belowelement="comment-35556" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to John D" aria-label='Reply to John D'>Reply</a>    </div>
