  <li id="comment-35600" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/18212980775962346075" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Laurel Bailey</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2012/01/i-am-here-to-tell-you/#comment-35600"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2012-09-09T22:16:37-04:00">Sunday, September 9, 2012 at 10:16 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I have been making and tweaking granola for years and had a house recipe down pat.  Then I stumbled upon your blog post and thought I&#39;d give it a try because I had not yet tried olive oil or coarse salt in my granola and I have to say, there is no need for another recipe EVER.  I haven&#39;t been able to locate the coconut chips so I just use medium, unsweetened, desiccated coconut, switch up the dried fruit and leave out the brown sugar altogether.  Fabulous! My husband and I agree that it is the best granola we&#39;ve had to date.  Thank you so much!</p>
    </div>

